                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d913">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24FLC/12–2245</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Thomas B. McCabe</persName> to
                        Brigadier General <persName type="to">Bernhard A. Johnson</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="94" xml:id="d913fn94">Deputy Field Commissioner, China Theater, Office
                        of the Foreign Liquidation Commissioner (OFLC). The OFLC was established in
                        the Department of State in October 1945 with responsibility for the
                        disposition of United States surplus property in foreign areas, Lend-Lease
                        matters, and liberated area requirements.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-12-22">22 December
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>War 89896. In view of State Dept. cable 31 [<hi rend="italic">2022</hi>] Dec.
                        19th,<note n="95" xml:id="d913fn95">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1376">p. 1376</ref>.</note>
                    please keep General Marshall<note n="96" xml:id="d913fn96">General of the Army
                        George C. Marshall, Special Representative of President Truman in
                        China.</note> fully informed on any conversation being carried on with
                    Chinese concerning Lend-Lease or surplus disposal.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
